	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Stats, prices, prices, stats, ....   BLEH<BR>
<BR>
I hate the way people are in this game.  &quot;Oh, I would NEVER pay 1200 pp for this item!&quot; one guy says. Yeah, no kiddin.  Probably because you're such a friggin moron you will never SEE 1200pp in your life.  To some people, these are worth 1200.  Prices are determined by supply and demand.  If you auction these for 1200 for a few days and nobody is inquiring, drop down to 1000.  If someone offers you 800, tell them you're considering other offers, but you'll keep them in mind.  <BR>
<BR>
The problems start when people get fixed ideas in their heads about an item's value, then start getting impatient and antsy to get it sold.  &quot;Come on, people, this is a *insert name of ultra-rare item here* I'm selling!  10 gazillion plat is a total bargain!&quot;  Keep in mind this is usually being spammed on /shout about every 20 seconds when there are only 18 people in the damn zone.<BR>
<BR>
It's almost like people are afraid to haggle.  Very, very few auctions have a price attached.  Usually it's the stock &quot;send tells with offers&quot;.  I suppose this is because people are so passive-aggressive that they want the buyer to make the first move.  I ALWAYS auction high.  It's funny as hell to auction a screaming mace for 200 plat in greater faydark.  I also always include &quot;or best offer&quot;, or the word &quot;flexible&quot;.  You'd still be surprised to see how many people /shout back &quot;Ha! No way it's worth that much!  I wouldn't pay 85!&quot;  My reply is, &quot;So are you offering 85? Because if you're not interested in buying it, why do you care what I'm selling it for?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Many other times someone will give me a /tell saying &quot;How much you want for the shiny brass shield?&quot;  &quot;40pp,&quot; I say. (I'm willing to take 15, 10 if they're nice).  &quot;Oh, never mind then.&quot; They say.  Now if they'd said, &quot;I only have 13pp to my name, and some bone chips&quot; Then, &quot;SOLD!&quot; says I.  It rarely gets that far. They oftentimes freak out on me, send me about 5 more tells telling me how much of a louse I am trying to rip off noobies, etc, etc.  Then they make the HUGE mistake of taking it to /shout or /ooc.  I eat these fools for lunch, it's funny.  Economics 99, EQ style.  Dr. Val at your service.  Heh, heh heh.<BR>
<BR>
It shouldn't be called an auction by the way, because there are so rarely two buyers competing for a purchase.  Cool items have become so common that it's like saying &quot;Listen up folks, I'm auctioning off this can of pork and beans tonight!  Bidding starts at 11 cents.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
I love the game, love the people.  I hate the parts of the game that allow worthless people to inflict their low IQs on the rest of us, namely the player-driven economy.  But I find my ways around it.  Like organizing a noobie raid on crushbone, where everybody in the zone goes out and makes a new wood elf or high elf character, meets in front of the orc lift, and storms into CB with reckless abandon by the dozens. The corpses get pretty dang thick!  (Alcohol is nice for this too).<BR>
<BR>
In order to close out my post with some pertinent information on the Azure Sleeves: they are sweet, they are some of the best lightweight AC items for arms in the game, and I'm shopping for them for my monk right now.  And AC 12 is PHENOMENAL for arm slots, whoever said it wasn't much to be excited about.<BR>
<BR>
Look for me tomorrow, for I shall be a grave lady.<BR>
Val. - enchanting orkies for twelve long years now<BR>
[Innoruuk server]<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Erollisi grant me the serenity to accept the things I cannot change, the courage to change the things I can, and the wisdom to know when to gate.&quot;
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
